{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Ke7wpDZAPtQjUsM2ZxScyY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still the same error, referencing the same old session path `session_2026-06-16_02-14-43_212834_13`. After deleting `/tmp/ray`, a new session with the same path is being found. This is very strange - it seems like the session information is coming from somewhere else.\n\nWait - looking at this more carefully: the session directory timestamp matches the ray-head startup time: `02-14-43`. The ray-head started at `2026-06-16 02:14:43`. \n\nSo when `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` is called, it connects to the ray-head at `ray-head:6379`, and the ray-head tells the client to use a session `session_2026-06-16_02-14-43_212834_13` (which is the ray-head's own session id), but then the client looks for this session locally in `/tmp/ray/` and can't find it.\nThis seems to be a fundamental issue with Ray 2.9.0 when connecting to a remote cluster - it's trying to locate node information files in a session directory that doesn't exist locally. Let me check the Ray source code to understand how it's attempting to find the node address.\n\nThe problem is that when I connect to the cluster with `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, Ray queries the GCS (the head node's state store) to get the session name, then tries to find that session directory locally on my machine. Even though I deleted `/tmp/ray`, it's still referencing the same session that was created on the head node, which doesn't exist in my local filesystem. CS returns the session ID, and Ray tries to locate the node IP address file in the session directory. The local raylet should be creating this file, but it seems like it's either not starting or failing to write it. Even after deleting `/tmp/ray`, the session directory persists because `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` retrieves the session from the GCS server rather than creating a fresh one