{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JTvsf7pWnahQBtKKGut7A9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The session directory is being created (with the lock file) but nothing else is being written. There are no log files at all. The raylet or the daemon is failing before it even writes any logs.\n\nLet me think about this differently. In Ray 2.9.0, when `ray.init(address='...')` is called on a client node, it:\n1. Connects to GCS\n2. Creates a session directory (gets session ID from GCS)\n3. Creates a lock file\n4. Starts a local raylet daemon process\n\nThe fact that no log files are created means the raylet subprocess is failing immediately. This could be:\n- Missing executables\n- `ulimit` / cgroup restrictions\n- A `--temp-dir` issue\n\nBut the warning about processes not registering with GCS suggests a different scenario. In Ray 2.x, connecting with `ray.init(address='...')` should work without starting a local raylet — the driver just connects to GCS and submits tasks. But something's going wrong with that connection path.\n\nLooking at the original command `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, this should connect as a pure driver to the existing cluster. The stack trace through `node.py` and `_wait_and_get_for_node_address()` suggests it's trying to initialize a local node when it shouldn't be, possibly due to a version mismatch between the Python environment on the ray-client and the cluster's Ray version.\n\nI'm wondering if the issue is simpler than I thought—maybe it's just a matter of which Python executable is being invoked when I run the command through kubectl. The anaconda Python 3.8 path in the error suggests there could be a mismatch between what's available in the container and what's expected.\n\nLooking at how Ray 2.9.0 handles `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, it goes through the worker initialization and tries to connect to an existing cluster by creating a Node with `head=False`. The problem seems to be that `_wait_and_get_for_node_address()` is waiting for a local `node_ip_address.json` file that should have been created by the head node, but it's not finding it.\n\nThe real issue is that even when connecting as a driver to a remote cluster, Ray 2.9.0 still needs a local raylet running to submit tasks. Without it, the driver can't schedule work on the cluster. So I need to figure out why the raylet isn't starting in the client container—it could be resource constraints, a missing binary, or some cgroup/seccomp issue. Let me try explicitly starting the raylet with `ray start --address=ray-head:6379` to join the cluster first.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":449,"cache_read_input_tokens":39151,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":449},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ac967dfd-b3a0-4c7b-9a8d-d78c19ca8fce","uuid":"dcade05f-ddf7-4b49-94eb-fa68da7f5e5b","request_id":"req_011Cc6gxWsQLGyoWQLu9LJng"}
